<br>
Now lets say you go to a auction system.  UberItemA drops.  Normally this items was set at 20points.  But now you auction it.  You have one guy at 60pts who has been doing all the guild raids and taking items that would help him help the guild.  Then you have another person with 50pts who hasn't been on many raids but never auctions on anything because he knows someday that UberItemA will drop and that is all he wants.  So now he uses all his points and the guy who really sould have it has to pay 50pts to get an item that is worth 20pts.<br>
<br>
Next case. There aren't many SK.  SK item drops.  Who is he going to bid against?  No one.  So he will be getting good stuff for hisself but not losing as many points as those that bid against each other (ie warriors).  So when that all/all item drops that everyone wants the SK has far more points than anyone else.  That isn't what I would call fair to the other people.<br>
<br>
<br>
At any rate.  My guild has taken up a modified version of this.  HOw do you deal with the fact that some classes aren't as needed on raids as others?  2-3 shaman is max for typical raids.  But you need tons of clerics and tons of mellee.  So the needed classes end up getting more points.  That leaves the other less needed classes out to dry.  HOw do you handle this?  Do you just say tough you aren't as needed thus aren't as important and won't get as many points as the needed classes?  That seems rather rude.  <br>
<br>
We had alot of people complaining that class_x will always have more points than class_y and that some way of normalizing the values between the two classes is needed to see who should get the item.  (ie 1 class_x point != 1 class_y point) Have you dealt with this at all? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/ucelandrospellsongtriton.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Celandro Spellsong     Triton</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#ffffff>(3/9/01 4:56:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub114.ezboard.com/flegacyofsteel43089general.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=891.topic&index=49>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: DKNY</span><hr size=1> <br>
&lt;BLOCKQUOTE&gt; Now lets say you go to a auction system. UberItemA drops. Normally this items was set at 20points. But now you auction it. You have one guy at 60pts who has been doing all the guild  raids and taking items that would help him help the guild. Then you have another person with 50pts who hasn't been on many raids but never auctions on anything because he knows someday that UberItemA will drop and that is all he wants. So now he uses all his points and the guy who really sould have it has to pay 50pts to get an item that is worth 20pts.&lt;/BLOCKQUOTE&gt;<br>
Smartass answer: well obviously if someone is willing to hoard and spend 50 points on an item worth 20 points then that item is really worth 50 points and not 20. If the person with more money doesnt want to pay the points that someone else wants to pay they do not deserve the item.<br>
Bit more logical answer: the person with 60 points has been collecting lots of items that help him. getting 1 more uber item over someone will fewer points will not help the guild any more than him getting a bunch of smaller items instead. And of course an item is worth whatever someone is willing to pay..<br>
<br>
<br>
&lt;BLOCKQUOTE&gt;Next case. There aren't many SK. SK item drops. Who is he going to bid against? No one. So he will be getting good stuff for hisself but not losing as many points as those that bid against each other (ie warriors). So when that all/all item drops that everyone wants the SK has far more points than anyone else. That isn't what I would call fair to the other people.&lt;/BLOCKQUOTE&gt;<br>
Well the SK items arent worth as much because they are class limited and not many people play SKs so of course he wont pay as much. As for when the all/all item drops, the SK will have fewer points than anyone else because he has been able to get every SK item that has dropped while others have gotten 0 items. Also the all/all item would have to be better than the SK specific item he probably has already. <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
&lt;BLOCKQUOTE&gt;At any rate. My guild has taken up a modified version of this. HOw do you deal with the fact that some classes aren't as needed on raids as others? 2-3 shaman is max for typical raids. But you  need tons of clerics and tons of mellee. So the needed classes end up getting more points. That leaves the other less needed classes out to dry. HOw do you handle this? Do you just say tough  you aren't as needed thus aren't as important and won't get as many points as the needed classes? That seems rather rude.&lt;BLOCKQUOTE&gt;<br>
This is exactly what Im talking about above. Those neccessary classes will be the ones who are most able to rack up the points because not enough items drop for them. This means they will be able to spend the most points on the uber uber items that drop. The &quot;unneeded&quot; classes will get plenty of their class specific items, lowering their points below a needed class who comes on every raid simply because the unneeded classes get the most loot.<br>
<br>
I think the analogy of points as money makes the most ammount of sense.. Set prices only work when there is a large enough supply that you can find what the true price of an item is. Auctions are designed by nature to handle those cases where items are relatively rare and determining a price for them is difficult (Just how much money is a red square painted on a white canvas worth? to me 0 but to an art collector.. probably in the millions). Supply and Demand IRL is solved by $. Really expensive and/or rare items are sold at auctions. There are also blind auctions and people bidding for other people in auctions. So long as the method of obtaining points is fair for all people, using auctions with DKP will be fair. Those with the most points can get the items if they really want it NO MATTER WHAT. However those with fewer points may have an opportunity to get an item they really want by bidding higher than those with more points.<br>
<br>
