Morell Thule<br><image src=http://www.followmearound.com/links/mirror3/grimreaper.gif></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/uthaelin.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Thaelin</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0 WIDTH=10 HEIGHT=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/19/01 4:14:05 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub114.ezboard.com/flegacyofsteel43089general.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=891.topic&index=57>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Economic Theory</span><hr size=1> I think Celandro hit the nail on the head, the beauty of the DKP system comes from how closely it approximates capitalist economic theory, with the auction system being the best way to set prices.<br>
<br>
The three main problems with the DKP system as Wendolyn describes it are a) item rot, b) determination of fair pricing, and c) point hording. Auctioning with reserve would do much to address both of those issues.<br>
<br>
a.) Everyone cringes when items rot, we know it's a waste. But it isn't fair to let someone get an item for &quot;free&quot; either. Placing a low &quot;reserve&quot; (minimum price) on items can help induce people to spend a small amount of points on something that they would watch decay under the currently dicussed DKP system. There can't really be any arguement that this would allow that one X class player in a guild to stock up on lots of class specific crap and still save up for the big stuff because if it's something that he would otherwise let rot, then it really has no value anyway. However, although the amount of points might be trivial in any specific circumstance, they would not be trivial in the aggregate. Thus, this player might actually find himself LESS able to horde under this system than if he watched a lot of items rot because of unreasonably high DKP cost. If it's truely something valuable, the reserve could be set somewhat higher.<br>
<br>
b) There's no fairer way to set prices than matching supply/demand through auction. This would mean that newer items might sell for a huge markup to their reserve as all the point horders cashed in their piggy banks, but prices would settle down once these players get what they want. This is a good thing as this just reflects the players with the most active participation getting the neat new toys first. At any rate, there could never be any arguements over the fairness of prices assigned to items. The person who places the highest value on an item, and has the participation to merit it, will get it.<br>
<br>
c) The problem with point hording, as I see it, isn't that people will skip items they might otherwise buy in order to save up for that one item they *really* want. This just means that the price on that one item is set too low (automatically corrected via auction.) If looting rights to the Dain's head are worth saving up say 150 DKP or more, then it's certainly worth spending a whole lot more than 20. The problem is that there is no mechanism to take those excessive points away. Think EQ's platinum economy. One problem this can create is that they are able to build up essentially permanent loot rights over newer members. No, it's not fair if a new member beats out an old hand for uber_item01, but it's not fair either if that new member faces the prospect of never being able to close the gap between himself and that older member. No matter how active a newer member is, he will always be inferior to longer serving members, even only slightly longer serving members, if they maintain the same level of raid participation. The prosect of upward mobility is a tremendous incentive. The auction system would drain those extra DKP's from the system, while at the same time retaining the reward for active participation. People are already in essence auctioning for the best items by saving up to see who can get the most DKP's. Why not make them actually spend those points too? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#212141><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/umorektherogue.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Morek the rogue</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/20/01 1:02:59 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub114.ezboard.com/flegacyofsteel43089general.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=891.topic&index=58>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Economic Theory</span><hr size=1> How would you go about giving points out to non-guilded members? There are times when someone may come on a raid as a guest. Are they just SOL when it comes to loot?<br>
